      <h3>A real forest, made small. <span class="it">A small world</span> a child can walk into.</h3>

      <div class="body">
        <p><span class="dropcap">T</span>he Woodland is built from real species. The deer family is a stag, a doe, and three fawns, one standing, one eating, one curled and sleeping. The trees are an oak, two birches, two firs, two acacias, two willows. Each is carved from a single piece of hardwood, painted by hand, finished with the kind of oil you can hold against a baby's cheek. There are no batteries. There are no instructions. The forest is the instructions.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="pillars">
        <div class="p"><span class="label">Habitat Studies</span><p>Real species, real proportions, real relationships.</p></div>
        <div class="p"><span class="label">Narrative Play</span><p>Family hierarchy, caregiving, the long quiet story.</p></div>
        <div class="p"><span class="label">Seasonal Awareness</span><p>Spring lime, summer moss, autumn rust, winter bare.</p></div>
        <div class="p"><span class="label">NGSS &middot; K&ndash;2</span><p>Life cycles, life science, place-based learning.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
